      {
        "id": 1691784,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-06-21T13:47:02.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I find this surprising. I haven\u2019t had the Beaux Monts from bottle, but I\u2019ve had the 2012 Chaumes, Petit Monts and Boudots this year, and all were exceptional\u2014and very typical of 2012 Vosne. Ditto the Grands Echezeaux last summer. You could open them alongside Vosne village and 1er crus from Cathiard, Mugneret Gibourg, Liger Belair, Hudelot Noellat etc without them standing out as remotely atypical. In style, they might be most similar to Cathiard though it\u2019s early days to say, and they seem a bit more savory, with the oak not so in your face. Perhaps the Beaux Monts is just a bit more shut down than the other cuv\u00e9es? It was certainly a stunner from barrel, and I confess I think the hype if anything understates how brilliant Maxime\u2019s wines are, especially when you consider his age and the fact that viticultural changes take time to show up in the finished wines.</p>",
